title: Integration with TF 2.0

labels.name: bug
labels.description: Indicates an unexpected problem or unintended behaviour

body:
I am trying to use the DeepExplainer with my Tensorflow model created using the model subclassing API. The model is a simply two-layer neural net. The code I run is as follows:

`e = shap.DeepExplainer(model, states)`

where states are the inputs of model for doing predictions. 

I receive the following error which makes me suspicious about the possibility to use the DeepExplainer with TF 2.0, but I am not able to find any reference to this in the doc. 


TypeError                                 Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-11-f5043446ac84> in <module>
      3 
      4 # explain predictions of the model on four images
----> 5 e = shap.DeepExplainer(model, background)
      6 # # ...or pass tensors directly
      7 # # e = shap.DeepExplainer((model.layers[0].input, model.layers[-1].output), background)

~\Anaconda3\envs\RLfin\lib\site-packages\shap\explainers\_deep\__init__.py in __init__(self, model, data, session, learning_phase_flags)
     78 
     79         if framework == 'tensorflow':
---> 80             self.explainer = TFDeep(model, data, session, learning_phase_flags)
     81         elif framework == 'pytorch':
     82             self.explainer = PyTorchDeep(model, data)

~\Anaconda3\envs\RLfin\lib\site-packages\shap\explainers\_deep\deep_tf.py in __init__(self, model, data, session, learning_phase_flags)
     95         # determine the model inputs and outputs
     96         self.model_inputs = _get_model_inputs(model)
---> 97         self.model_output = _get_model_output(model)
     98         assert type(self.model_output) != list, "The model output to be explained must be a single tensor!"
     99         assert len(self.model_output.shape) < 3, "The model output must be a vector or a single value!"

~\Anaconda3\envs\RLfin\lib\site-packages\shap\explainers\tf_utils.py in _get_model_output(model)
     81         isinstance(model, tf.keras.Model):
     82         if len(model.layers[-1]._inbound_nodes) == 0:
---> 83             if len(model.outputs) > 1:
     84                 warnings.warn("Only one model output supported.")
     85             return model.outputs[0]

TypeError: object of type 'NoneType' has no len()
